Quae-est? “what stain of domestic insamy has not been branded on your life? '' Distinguish: murz, ηόιᾶ, nimi. The expression nota domesticae turpitudinis differs in meaning from privatarum rerum dedecus: the former relates to moral or immoral domestic life, the latter to all private actions as op- posed to those that affect a man's public character. Nota is applied (1) to the brand on cattle ; Virg. Georg. 3, 158 : (2) to the mark placed on a fugitive slave when retakeu z (3) to the mark placed by the censor (nota cen-soria) on revising the list of citizens, opposite the name os the person degraded. Accord- ing to Plutarch, Catiliue had slain his own brother and murdered his own son that there might be no obstacle to his marrying Aurelia Orestilla.
